metadata.name: thébaïde #84
metadata.description:
“Thébaïde” is a french word for wild place, remote and peaceful, where to live in a calm retreat. It's also simply a desert and a synonym of solitude. It comes from Thebaid, an arid region of ancient Egypt and Thebes was the capital.

“thébaïde” is my debut on fx(hash), almost one year since my first works minted on Objkt (a series of Indian ink drawings, in January 2022). After learning the basics of creative coding recently, and a few works with this technique, I decided to create a first generative project. With "thébaïde" I chose to express the minimalist and narrative aspects of my artistic approach (though the title and concept emerged at the end). Gradually the work was resonating with philosophical matters I'm obsessed with since years: time, emptiness, human condition, erosion, desire, chance, combining them into a visual metaphor. The view of a vast area, a changing silhouette, an impenetrable monolith or an opening to elsewhere or nothing, day and night and day and night and dawn and dusk — few elements able to compose a meditative and lasting tableau of questions and feelings.

Press “s” in live mode to save the work.
Made with p5js | 2023
Png | 2000 px x 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.com

metadata.name: Type-o-Graphic #79
metadata.description:
Type-o-Graphic embraces the ethos of David Carson's groundbreaking graphic design work. It explores the intersections of typography, design, art and chance, harnessing the power of randomness to create a series of posters that are a frenetic celebration of typographic chaos.

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning — several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

Features:
B - Toggle border
N - Change border colour
K - Change background colour (if visible)
T - Toggle top finish (if applicable)
Up/Down - Change colour palette (43)
Left/Right - Change blend modes (20)
L - Change to Landscape
P - Change to Portrait
S - Save image

0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 - Change resolution of image
0 - 600 x 900 - (low-res)
1 - 1200 x 1800 - 4x6" @ 300dpi - (default)
2 - 2400 x 3600 - 8x12" @ 300dpi
3 - 3600 x 5400 – 12x18" @ 300dpi
4 - 4800 x 7200 - 16x24" @ 300dpi
5 - 7200 x 10800 - 24x36" @ 300dpi

See accompanying article for more info:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/type-o-graphic

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2023
Follow me on twitter or instagram @fauxjebus

metadata.name: seekers #271
metadata.description:
Seekers is inspired by the view that is held by mathematical realism, that mathematical entities objectively exist independently of the human mind. Therefore, mathematical entities are not constructed by humans, but rather, are discovered by humans. This means, that also other intelligent beings would be able to discover the same entities.

In 'seekers', a set of complicated, computer-generated functions are used to render coloured spaces on a Cartesian plane. The mathematical space is being explored and discovered by a group of seekers, which hover and fly around within the layers of infinitely evolving shapes. The vicinity of a seeker also modifies the surrounding mathematical space, which means that the seekers will never reach the objective reality.

The generating functions are created using human-curated evolutionary algorithm following the idea demonstrated already in Karl Sims' paper 'Artificial Evolution for Computer Graphics' in 1991.

———

Features 29 generative base functions, 15 palettes in various modes. Some palettes have a special 'dark mode', where the seekers also slightly illuminate the otherwise darkened space.

----

Notes for viewer:

- The piece adapts to all screen sizes, although a fixed size can be defined by url parameters.

- The piece is preferably viewed full-screen. The resolution can be adjusted for best performance.

- The piece can be paused and high-resolution stills can be exported for printing.

- Video clips can be exported in webm format. For a high-resolution video, frames should be batch exported as PNG-sequence and rendered in a video editing software.

----

Controls: 

- Number keys from [1] to [8] adjust the resolution
- [space] pauses animation
- [s] exports a PNG with the current resolution
- [x] starts and stops recording of a webm clip (25mbps)
- [i] toggles display of frame number and resolution

----

URL parameters:

- &width={WIDTH}&height={HEIGHT} explicitly sets the render resolution to {WIDTH}x{HEIGHT}. Resolution controls do not work when dimensions are explicitly set.

- &rec={start},{end} batch records frames starting from {start} and ending at {end}. Can also be used to record stills. For example, if you want a still export from frame 300 in resolution 5000x3000, you can start the piece with url parameters &width=5000&height=3000&rec=300,300

----

metadata.name: STRUCTURES #19
metadata.description:
STRUCTURES

What color do things look when you're happy?

First of all I want to dedicate this collection to all the people who paint their emotions with color, who through a chromatic range, are capable of feeling a universe of sensations most of the time inexplicable.....

 I am fascinated by how generative art creates a perfect symbiosis between art and technology, allowing through a set of algorithmic rules to give rise to compositions where shapes and colors coexist in balance, harmonized with each other that give rise to new creations.

This collection is designed to be self-contained and limited, recreating the view from different angles and phases of the day that can lead to disparate interpretations of a piece.

My work as a visual artist explores elements such as randomness and chance of linear formations and geometric gradients that broaden the spectrum to increasingly new concepts that I definitely want to explore.

I continually wonder what the geometric patterns that will emerge from my sensibility will be like and will give rise to new collections like this one, which is why I continue to investigate techniques and shapes while having fun.

"A painting is not the image of an experience, but it is the experience." Mark Rothk

metadata.name: Point(); Line(); Plane(); #70
metadata.description:
The title of this piece is a reference to Wassily Kandisky's book "Point and Line to Plane" (1926).

Eight points are placed at random positions, assigned a color and direction, and moved, to become lines. These lines are then translated to form planes.

This idea was already formulated by Aristotle: "a line by its motion produces a surface, and a point by its motion a line".

This simple algorithm creates an interesting variety of compositions, all unique and recognizable.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be exported by pressing "s".

PNG exports can be obtained by pressing "1" (3300×1900) or "2" (6600×3800).

metadata.name: Tangentum #173
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Nebula, Solitude #6
metadata.description:
Nebula is one of the most magnificent stellar phenomena to behold. It is a distinct luminescent part of the interstellar medium, which consists of ionized gas and cosmic dust. Nebulae are often star-forming regions, where stars are born in solitude but surrounded by beautiful light and matter.

In this series, I continue the exploration of color and gravity, the effect of mass on speed, the effect of speed on hue, and how light can change by passing through big particles and dust systems.

I also want to let you participate in the creation of your artwork variation too. Each iteration is a unique and unpredictable dance of light in the dust and gravitation between matter clusters, however,  with the controls listed below, you can change the probability of light/dust blocks as well as the tiling layout.

[L] - create a new layout
[S] - reshuffle the current layout

[Shift] + [1] - change dust blocks probability to 0.0 and reshuffle the current layout
[Shift] + [2] - —//— 0.2
[Shift] + [3] - —//— 0.4
[Shift] + [4] - —//— 0.6
[Shift] + [5] - —//— 0.8
[Shift] + [6] - —//— 1.0

Basics:
[A] - skip/restart the animation

[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Experimental zone:
[E] - toggle endless animation
[0] - save the current frame in low resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.

Use Chrome 107 for the best experience, other browsers are significantly slower on this artwork, visual results also may vary.

Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Special Token [RESERVE PASS] #7
metadata.description:
Back when I was a researcher at a human-computer interaction lab, I parked in the adjacent neighborhood and rode the city bus into campus.

Usually this was a pretty uneventful affair.

One spring day though, the bus was packed and I had to stand right up front by the driver. Despite trying to appear busy enough not to be bothered, the driver struck up a conversation.

At some point in the short trip, we stopped at a red light. It was then that he made an off-hand comment that I've remembered ever since.

“The moment between when the light turns green and when I realize it, that’s where my soul resides.”

I’m not sure how you’re supposed to respond to that. But nevertheless it smacked me.

So: do not consider each of these my personal signature as an artist, developer, and tinkerer.

Do consider them an expended shard of my soul and the culmination of experiences that have led up to this moment.

This is the light turning green.

---

THIS TOKEN IS A RESERVE PASS (it’s ✨special✨)

- This token will function as a reserve pass for any future drop on fx(hash) that has a total edition size of > 100 (ie, most of my drops, other than dedicated “sketch” projects that may have intentionally fewer editions)

- Future reserves will be limited to holders of this token, and holding this token will guarantee you a dedicated 24 hour reserve spot on such projects.

- Holding any token from my prior projects will make you eligible to mint from this drop (I will take a final snapshot ~1 hr prior to drop).

- I have created an edition size of 60, but only 40 will be open for minting at this time. I’ll reserve the remainder for issuing or burning at my discretion.

- I will also airdrop ~9 editions to the top collectors of my previous projects (consider Twitter to be the source of info on this prior to the drop)

WHY?

I don’t like the idea of picking and choosing who gets a reserve and who doesn’t.

I love you all 🙏

---

- Made with p5JS
- Press “s” to save png

metadata.name: Abstract Comic #17
metadata.description:
Comics were the trigger for my first absolute rapture. It was so intense that I couldn't wait to get home from school to dive into my secret box of comics and, for a few hours, escape to the world of superheroes. And, at least for a short time, be taken away from reality in which I was ostracized from society at school only because I liked math, and because I thought Spiderman and Batman were cool.

Decades later, the only thing that can be compared to the appearance of comics is the discovery of generative art. I haven't felt such a boyish trance since the appearance of the comics. And nothing has come more naturally than trying to unite my two loves.

This piece tries to achieve a comic vibe using abstract shapes and tries to convey the texture of the paper, which was of poor quality but had the most beautiful smell in the world. It was a challenge to create dynamics, action, movement, fight, and childlike joy all at the same time. Each color palette is inspired by some of the most famous comic book heroes and villains. But by far the biggest challenge was making this piece a direct link to childhood for all of you.

I sincerely hope that I succeeded.


Options:

- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 'd' to save a hi-res PNG image

Created using p5.js
Bajiru, January 2023.
